          unity - access UNITY DBMS commands

     SSSSYYYYNNNNOOOOPPPPSSSSIIIISSSS
          unity [----vvvv] [----rrrr]

     DDDDEEEESSSSCCCCRRRRIIIIPPPPTTTTIIIIOOOONNNN
          _U_n_i_t_y appends the path name $TOOLS/lib/unity/bin to the
          current $PATH value, changes the primary shell prompt to
          ``unity> '' and executes a new shell.

          $UNITYDFILES is set to $TOOLS/lib/unity/lib if not already
          set allowing access to canned descriptor files for the fol-
          lowing:

               /etc/passwd
               /etc/group
               /usr/asp/log/oprlog
               /usr/asp/log/usendlog
               /usr/asp/log/unpacklog

          In addition, the dbfiles and overview files used in uuuummmmeeeennnnuuuu.
          are also stored in this directory.

          The $TOOLS/lib/unity/bin directory contains all of the UNITY
          commands.

          If the ----rrrr option is given, access to the UNITY commands is
          created in a restricted environment; that is, $PATH is set
          to :/rbin:/usr/rbin:/bin:/usr/bin:$TOOLS/lib/unity/bin and
          the restricted shell, _r_s_h, is invoked. To restore the
          environment that existed prior to issuing the _u_n_i_t_y command,
          type EOT (control-d).

          The ----vvvv option prints the version of UNITY.

          A manual page for each of the UNITY commands can be gen-
          erated by typing:

               toolman "command name"

          in the _u_n_i_t_y environment or:

               toolman -Dunity '*'

          outside of _u_n_i_t_y to produce the entire UNITY manual.

          In order to obtain an overview of UNITY, along with a brief
          summary of the syntax of all the commands type:

               toolman Intro




